\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\fs32 Files and Folders
\par \cf2\f1\fs20 Files and Folders structure of Kitto2 project\cf3\fs22\{keepn\}\cf2 
\par 
\par \pard\tx200\b0\fs20 Kide2 editor\f0  uses files of a Kitto2 Projects stored on file system with a special structure. In the left of the \cf4\strike main window\cf3\strike0\{linkID=1140\}\cf2  you can manage files and resources.
\par 
\par \pard\b\f1\fs22 Kitto2 metadata structure\b0\f0\fs20 
\par \pard\tx200 Most of a Kitto2 application lies in the metadata files.
\par All metadata files are in \cf1\strike yaml\cf3\strike0\f2\{link=*! ExecFile("http://www.yaml.org/")\}\cf2\f0  format. 
\par Yaml is a human-readable markup language which is easier to read and less noisy and error-prone to write than XML or JSON, meaning that you can just open and edit the files in your preferred text editor. 
\par Just remember:
\par A yaml file is a tree of nodes, each on its own text line with a name followed by a colon followed by a value.
\par Valid data types for values include numbers, strings, dates but also space-separated lists and special values or macros. Multi-line values are supported as well.
\par Indentation in yaml is paramount to define structure. Kitto, by convention, uses two spaces for each level of indentation.
\par \pard For more informations, visit: \cf1\strike\f2 Wiki: Basic concepts\cf3\strike0\{link=*! ExecFile("https://github.com/EtheaDev/kitto2/wiki/BasicConcepts")\}\cf2\f0 
\par \b\f1\fs22 Metadata directory structure
\par \cf3\b0\fs20\{bmc FilesMetadata.jpg\}\cf2 
\par The Metadata directory contains one or more config files (by default, one called Config.yaml) and some subdirectories with more yaml files. Currently you have:
\par Models containing one yaml file for each model, which is basically the representation of a database table (although it can be more abstract than that).
\par Views containing one yaml file for each view, which is a piece of user interface, often linked to an underlying model or family of models.\f0 
\par \b\fs22 
\par Resources
\par \cf3\b0\f1\fs20\{bmc FilesResources.jpg\}\cf2 
\par Resources are just additional files that your application will need to send to the web browser, such as images and javascript files, while the Delphi project contains any server-side business logic you might need to implement.
\par 
\par \f0 Form more information about Kitto2 Files and Folders structure visit: \cf1\strike kitto/wiki/BasicConcepts\cf3\strike0\f2\{link=*! ExecFile("https://github.com/nandod/kitto/wiki/BasicConcepts")\}\cf2\f1 
\par }
